Lepage  .","French Canadian (<b>Pagé</b>): altered form of French   Paget  , a diminutive of 1. Compare   Pashia  .","North German: metonymic occupational name for a horse dealer, from Middle Low German <i>page</i> ‘horse’."],"variants":[{"name":"Pages","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Mario, Eduardo, Jorge, Luis, Mauricio, Ramon, Fernando, Jose, Lazaro, Pedro, Alfredo.  French Jacques, Lucien, Michel.","Catalan and southern French (<b>Pagès</b>): occupational name for a peasant farmer or agricultural laborer, from Catalan and Old Occitan <i>pagès</i> ‘peasant’ (from Late Latin <i>pagensis</i>, a derivative of <i>pagus</i> ‘village, country district’).","English: variant of   Page   with genitival of post-medieval excrescent <i>s</i>."]},{"name":"Paget","meanings":["French: diminutive of   Page  .","English: variant of   Padgett  ."]},{"name":"Paige","meanings":["English (mainly Devon): variant of   Page  ."]},{"name":"Pageau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Stephane, Alphonse, Andre, Fernand, Gisele, Jean Claude, Lucien, Philippe.","French: diminutive of   Page  ."]},{"name":"Lepage","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Andre, Fernand, Pierre, Raoul, Adelard, Alcide, Christophe, Lucien, Normand, Adrien.","French: occupational or status name for a young servant, a variant of   Page   1, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. Compare   Lapage  .","French Canadian: altered form of <b>Pagé</b> (see   Page   2)."]},{"name":"Padgett","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire): from a Middle English diminutive of <i>page</i>, <i>paige</i> ‘servant, groom’ (see   Page  )."]},{"name":"Littlepage","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>littel</i> ‘small’ +Middle English, Old French <i>page</i> ‘young servant’ (see   Page  )."]},{"name":"Pashia","meanings":["Americanized form of French Canadian <b>Pagé</b> (see   Page   2).","History: It was Jean Baptiste Pagé from QC whose surname was changed to <i>Pashia</i> after he settled in MO in the 1810s. Some of his descendants bear a rare variant, <i>Pashea</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":6,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":15,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":26,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":28,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":42,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":44,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Page was born in 1543, in Acle, Norfolk, England. He married Martha in 1574, in Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He was buried in Acle, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1543–1587":"1543–1587","1546–Female":"1546–Surnud","1575–Male":"1575–Surnud","1577–1617":"1577–1617","1579–Female":"1579–Surnud","1582–1615":"1582–1615","1571":"1571","1582":"1582","       1577":"11. jaanuar 1577 kuni 10. jaanuar 1578","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1579":"1579","1546":"1546","1577":"1577","1543":"1543","1